.\" wt(1) — Git Worktree Manager
.\" vim: set ft=groff:
.TH WT 1 "2025" "wt 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.\"
.\" ── Colour palette ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
.if \n(.g \{\
.  defcolor teal   rgb #00AFAF
.  defcolor amber  rgb #D7AF00
.  defcolor plum   rgb #AF87AF
.  defcolor sky    rgb #5F87AF
.  defcolor lime   rgb #5FAF5F
.  defcolor dim    rgb #878787
.  defcolor brick  rgb #AF5F5F
.\}
.\"
.\" Inline colour macros
.de Cm
.  ie \n(.g \m[teal]\fB\\$*\fP\m[]
.  el \fB\\$*\fP
..
.de Fl
.  ie \n(.g \m[amber]\fB\\$*\fP\m[]
.  el \fB\\$*\fP
..
.de Ci
.  ie \n(.g \m[plum]\fI\\$*\fP\m[]
.  el \fI\\$*\fP
..
.de Pa
.  ie \n(.g \m[sky]\\$*\m[]
.  el \fI\\$*\fP
..
.de Di
.  ie \n(.g \m[dim]\\$*\m[]
.  el \\$*
..
.\"
.\" Tag-line string escapes (used directly on .TP tag lines)
.ds Ct \m[teal]\fB
.ds Ce \fP\m[]
.ds At \m[amber]\fB
.ds Ae \fP\m[]
.ds Pt \m[plum]\fI
.ds Pe \fP\m[]
.ds Dt \m[dim]
.ds De \m[]
.\"
.\" ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH NAME
\m[teal]\fBwt\fP\m[] \(em minimal Git worktree manager with auto-cd support
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B wt
.I <command>
.RI [ \-f ]
.RI [ \-D ]
.RI [ arguments ]
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B wt
is a thin wrapper around
.BR git-worktree (1)
that enforces a consistent directory layout, sanitizes branch names,
auto-registers an ignore rule, and \(em when the shell wrapper is
installed \(em automatically changes the current directory after
worktree operations.
.PP
All linked worktrees are created under:
.RS
.Pa <repo-root>/.worktree/<repo-name>.<sanitized-ref>
.RE
.PP
.B wt
works from any directory inside the repository \(em the main root,
inside a linked worktree, or inside the
.Pa .worktree/
container directory itself.
.\"
.SH SHELL SETUP
.B wt
cannot change the directory of its parent shell process on its own.
Install the shell wrapper by adding the following to
.Pa ~/.bashrc
or
.Pa ~/.zshrc :
.PP
.RS
.EX
eval "$(wt init)"
.EE
.RE
.PP
This defines a shell function that invokes the binary
.I once ,
strips the internal cd directive from stdout, and calls
.BR cd (1)
in the current shell.  Compatible with both
.BR bash (1)
and
.BR zsh (1).
.\"
.SH COMMANDS
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctinit\*(Ce
Print the shell function definition to standard output.
Intended for:
.RS
.EX
eval "$(wt init)"
.EE
.RE
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctadd\*(Ce \*(Pt<branch|commit-ish>\*(Pe
Create a new linked worktree and cd into it.
.PP
.RS
Resolution order:
.RS
.IP "1." 4
.B Local branch exists
\(em checked out on that branch.
.IP "2." 4
.B Valid \c
.Ci commit-ish
(tag, full SHA, short SHA,
.Ci HEAD~N ,
remote ref, \(el)
\(em created with
.BR \-\-detach .
.IP "3." 4
.B Unknown name
\(em a new local branch is created.
.RE
.PP
Running
.Cm add
on an already-existing worktree is idempotent: it cds into the
existing path without error.
.RE
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctrm\*(Ce [\*(At\-f\*(Ae] [\*(At\-D\*(Ae] \*(Dt[\*(De\*(Pt<n>\*(Pe\*(Dt]\*(De
Remove a linked worktree.
Without
.Ci <n> ,
removes the worktree the shell is currently inside and returns to the
main worktree root.
With
.Ci <n> ,
removes that specific worktree.
Resolution scans
.Pa .worktree/
on disk, so it is immune to remote-URL or directory renames.
.PP
.RS
.B Uncommitted changes.
If the worktree has uncommitted changes and
.Fl \-f
is not supplied,
.B wt
prints the changed files and prompts:
.EX
Remove anyway? [y/N]
.EE
Answering
.B n
or pressing Enter aborts without touching anything.
Answering
.B y
proceeds with force removal.
When no controlling terminal is available (non-interactive / CI),
.B wt
refuses and exits 1; pass
.Fl \-f
explicitly to skip the check.
.PP
.B Branch deletion.
After the worktree is removed,
if
.Fl \-D
is not supplied and the worktree was on a local branch,
.B wt
prompts:
.EX
Delete branch <branch>? [y/N]
.EE
Answering
.B y
deletes the branch.
Any other answer \(em or no controlling terminal \(em leaves the
branch untouched (safe default).
.PP
.Fl \-D
skips the prompt and always deletes the branch.
Silently skipped for detached-HEAD worktrees (no branch to delete).
.RE
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctco\*(Ce \*(Pt<n>\*(Pe
Change directory into an existing worktree.
The worktree must already exist; use
.Cm add
first.
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctls\*(Ce
Display all worktrees.
The current worktree is marked with \(bu and highlighted.
Each row shows the directory name, abbreviated HEAD SHA (7 chars),
and branch name \(em or
.Ci "HEAD (detached)"
for detached-HEAD worktrees.
A
.B [main]
badge is appended at the end of the main worktree row, keeping
SHA and branch columns aligned across all rows.
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctmv\*(Ce [\*(At\-D\*(Ae] \*(Pt<from>\*(Pe \*(Pt<to>\*(Pe
Move (rename) the worktree identified by
.Ci <from>
to the path derived from
.Ci <to> .
The destination uses the same name prefix as the source.
If the shell is inside the source worktree, it is redirected to
the new path automatically.
.PP
.RS
.Fl \-D
renames the associated local branch from
.Ci <from>
to
.Ci <to>
using
.BR "git branch \-m" .
Warns and exits 0 for detached-HEAD worktrees.
.RE
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctprune\*(Ce
Run
.B git worktree prune
to remove stale metadata for worktrees no longer on disk.
.\"
.TP
\*(Ctnuke\*(Ce [\*(At\-f\*(Ae] [\*(At\-D\*(Ae]
Remove
.I all
linked worktrees.
Prompts for confirmation unless
.Fl \-f
is supplied.
If the shell is inside any removed worktree it is returned to the
main root.
.PP
.RS
Without
.Fl \-D ,
only the worktree directories are removed; branches are
.B kept .
.PP
.Fl \-D
additionally deletes the associated local branch for each worktree.
Detached-HEAD worktrees are silently skipped.
.RE
.\"
.SH FLAGS
.TP
\*(At\-f\*(Ae, \*(At\-\-force\*(Ae
For
.Cm rm :
skip the uncommitted-changes prompt and force removal.
For
.Cm nuke :
skip the confirmation prompt.
.TP
\*(At\-D\*(Ae, \*(At\-\-delete-branch\*(Ae
Additionally manage the associated branch:
.RS
.TP
.Cm rm
Delete the branch after removing the worktree.
Skips the interactive branch-deletion prompt.
.TP
.Cm mv
Rename the branch to match the new worktree name.
.TP
.Cm nuke
Delete every branch belonging to a removed worktree.
.RE
.\"
.SH BRANCH SANITIZATION
Both branch names and commit-ish references are sanitized before
being used as directory suffixes:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B /
replaced with
.B \-
.IP \(bu 2
Any non-alphanumeric, non-dot, non-hyphen, non-underscore character
replaced with
.B \-
.IP \(bu 2
Leading and trailing hyphens stripped
.IP \(bu 2
Consecutive hyphens collapsed to one
.RE
.PP
.TS
l l l .
\m[teal]feature/login\m[]	\(->\~\~\m[sky]myrepo.feature-login\m[]
\m[teal]fix/bug@1.0\m[]	\(->\~\~\m[sky]myrepo.fix-bug-1.0\m[]
\m[plum]v3.2.2\m[]	\(->\~\~\m[sky]myrepo.v3.2.2\m[]
\m[plum]388d460\m[]	\(->\~\~\m[sky]myrepo.388d460\m[]
\m[plum]release/v2.0\m[]	\(->\~\~\m[sky]myrepo.release-v2.0\m[]
.TE
.\"
.SH WORKTREE RESOLUTION
For
.Cm rm ,
.Cm co ,
and
.Cm mv ,
.B wt
scans
.Pa .worktree/
on disk and matches by sanitized suffix.
This makes resolution correct even after the repository directory
is renamed, moved, or the origin remote URL changes.
.\"
.SH COLOUR PALETTE
.TS
lB l .
\m[teal]Teal\m[]	command names, info arrows (\(->), active branch in \fBls\fP
\m[amber]Amber\m[]	flags (\fB\-f\fP, \fB\-D\fP) and warnings (\[u26A0])
\m[plum]Plum\m[]	commit-ish refs, tags, SHAs, detached HEAD state
\m[sky]Sky\m[]	file paths, directory names, non-active branch names
\m[lime]Lime\m[]	success (\[u2713]), active worktree marker (\[u25B6])
\m[dim]Dim\m[]	secondary / muted text (SHAs in \fBls\fP, hints)
\m[brick]Brick\m[]	errors
.TE
.PP
Colours are suppressed when
.B NO_COLOR
is set to any non-empty value
.RI ( https://no-color.org )
or when
.B TERM
is
.B dumb
or unset.
.\"
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
Disable all ANSI colour output when set to any non-empty value.
.TP
.B TERM
Used to detect whether colour output is appropriate.
Colours are disabled when this is
.B dumb
or unset.
.TP
.B WT_NO_PROMPT
When set to
.B 1 ,
all interactive prompts are suppressed without reading from the terminal.
The safe default is taken for each prompt:
the uncommitted-changes check aborts with exit 1 (same as no controlling
terminal), and the branch-deletion prompt is skipped (branch kept).
Intended for use in CI pipelines and automated scripts.
Pass
.Fl \-f
and/or
.Fl \-D
explicitly to control behaviour in non-interactive contexts.
.\"
.SH FILES
.TP
.Pa <repo-root>/.worktree/
Directory that holds all linked worktrees managed by
.BR wt .
.TP
.Pa <repo-root>/.git/info/exclude
Receives the entry
.B /.worktree
on first use (idempotent).
.\"
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Usage error, missing worktree, aborted prompt, or underlying
.BR git (1)
failure.
A diagnostic message is written to standard error.
.\"
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS One-time setup
.EX
echo 'eval "$(wt init)"' >> ~/.zshrc
source ~/.zshrc
.EE
.SS Branch worktrees
.EX
wt add feature/payments   # new branch -> cd into worktree
wt add fix/typo           # another branch
wt ls                     # list all worktrees
wt co feature/payments    # cd into existing worktree
wt rm                     # remove current, prompt for branch, cd to main
wt rm -D feature/old      # remove + delete branch (no prompt)
.EE
.SS Detached-HEAD worktrees (tag / SHA)
.EX
wt add v3.2.2             # tag -> .worktree/myrepo.v3.2.2  (detached)
wt add 388d460            # SHA -> .worktree/myrepo.388d460 (detached)
wt rm v3.2.2              # remove (no branch, no prompt)
.EE
.SS Dirty worktree
.EX
wt rm feature/wip         # shows changed files, prompts to confirm
wt rm -f feature/wip      # force-remove, no prompt
.EE
.SS Rename
.EX
wt mv feature/old feature/new      # rename dir only
wt mv -D feature/old feature/new   # rename dir + rename branch
.EE
.SS Tear down
.EX
wt nuke           # confirm, then remove all worktrees (branches kept)
wt nuke -D        # confirm, then remove all + delete branches
wt nuke -f -D     # same, skip confirmation
.EE
.SS Non-interactive / CI
.EX
# Use explicit flags to avoid prompts; or set WT_NO_PROMPT=1.
wt rm -f -D feature/done          # force-remove + delete branch
WT_NO_PROMPT=1 wt rm feature/done # same safe-default behaviour
.EE
.\"
.SH TESTING
A test suite ships alongside the binary:
.EX
bash wt_test.sh              # uses ./wt in same directory
bash wt_test.sh /path/to/wt
WT_BIN=/usr/local/bin/wt bash wt_test.sh
.EE
The suite is fully automated: it sets
.B WT_NO_PROMPT=1
internally so no test ever blocks on a terminal prompt.
.\"
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR git-worktree (1),
.BR git (1)
.\"
